<TITLE> Stocks finish flat </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 28 (bdnews24.com)Stocks ended nearly flat on the closing day of the week as retail investors were keen to lock in profits, while institutional ones continued buying in the wake of lowered prices. The benchmark DGEN or general index edged up 2.29 points, or 0.83 percent, to end on 2765.45. The DSI or all-share price index finished 3.25 points, or 0.13 percent, up at 2369.11. The blue-chip DSE-20 crept up 1.93 points, or 0.07 percent, to 2425.88. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended flat with indices edging down as huge losses in banks and non-bank financial institutions were countered by insurance scrips that witnessed the largest gains. The CSCX or selective categories index lost 5.37 points, or 0.09 percent, to close on 5609.41. The CASPI or all-share price index closed at 8593.38, down by 6.93 points or 0.08 percent. The bourse's blue-chip CSE-30 fell 8.41 points, or 0.10 percent, to end on 7845.11. Sell-offs at the opening bell led Dhaka stocks to slump. It started to recover losses in midday trade as institutional investors went on buying, an official of Lanka Bangla Securities told bdnews24.com. Meanwhile, lower investor participation especially retail buyers, caused turnover and trading volume to fall from the previous day. Turnover on the DSE reached Tk 2.46 billion, with 13,713,646 shares changing hands, while the port city bourse saw 2,970,041 traded shares amounting to Tk 406.414 million in turnover. Losers beat gainers on the DSE by 115 to 100, while ten issues held steady. Of the traded 141 issues on the CSE, 82 lost, 51 gained, and eight remained unchanged. State owned Titas Gas emerged as the turnover leader on the DSE with a 3.37 percent gain from the previous day, closing at Tk 375.50. Second in line, Beximco Pharma lost 2.95 percent to Tk 111.80 after investors locked in profits. Islami Bank slipped 0.82 percent to finish at Tk 7778.50. Selling pressure led Beximco to end on Tk 112.40, down by 2.26 percent while AB Bank gained 1.01 percent to Tk 999.25. Among the other scrips on the turnover board--Square Textiles, Square Pharmaceuticals, and Prime Life Insurance -- gained. Lanka Bangla Finance and Uttara Bank lost on profit taking
